    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey, i have a physics exam coming up and i'm a bit stuck on quantum entanglement. can you give me a quick, non-math summary of what it actually is? also i'm confused about how it's different from just regular classical correlation. thanks",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is a phenomenon where two or more particles become interconnected in such a way that the state of one particle instantly influences the state of the other, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine you have two entangled particles, like two magical, invisible strings that are connected. If you tug on one, the other one will instantly react, even if it's on the other side of the universe. This is unlike classical correlation, where things are more like two friends who occasionally chat and share information, but their actions are not instant and not as deeply connected. In classical correlation, you can only predict the behavior of one friend if you know the behavior of the other, but it's not a magical, instant connection. In quantum entanglement, it's like having a pair of enchanted dice that always roll the same number, no matter how far apart they are.",
