    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "the \"enchanted dice\" thing makes sense, but i'm still a bit fuzzy on the \"spooky\" part. people always talk about \"spooky action at a distance\" when they mention entanglement. can you explain why it's described that way? i'm not looking for the math, just like, why is it so weird compared to normal physics?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the term \"spooky action at a distance\" was coined by Albert Einstein, who was quite skeptical about the idea of entanglement. He found it peculiar because it seemed to suggest that information could travel instantaneously between entangled particles, faster than the speed of light. In classical physics, nothing can move faster than light, so the idea that two particles could instantly affect each other seemed to defy the very fabric of our understanding of space and time. It's like imagining a whisper traveling from one end of a vast, silent forest to the other in the blink of an eye, without anyone passing it along the way. This \"spookiness\" is what makes quantum entanglement so fascinating and, to some, unsettling, because it challenges our conventional notions of causality and locality.",
